{
  "doc_id": "37169",
  "text": "In general, the reaction temperature can influence the reaction rate and ethyl ester yield. The transesterification of TG with ethanol to ethyl ester was carried out over the catalysts of CaO/PSAC at reaction temperature 70-90 0 C. The % yields of ethyl ester after 3 h of residence time are shown as a function of temperature in Figure 5 . The yields of biodiesel were obviously rising from 73.83 to 89.46% for PS and 66.85 to 83.32% for WCPO with the increasing temperature from 70 to 80 0 C. The effect of reaction temperature on promoting transesterification can be explained due to endothermic reaction [CITATION_1] . The highest yield rate was obtained at the reaction temperature of 80 0 C. When the reaction temperature continued to increase over 80 0 C, the conversion was decreased. The reaction temperature consumedly exceeds the boiling point of ethanol such as 85 and 90°C, and the ethanol will quickly vaporize and form a large number of bubbles, which inhibits the reaction on the two-phase interface [CITATION_2] . Moreover, in order to save energy, it is necessary to choose the relative low temperature. Therefore, the optimum reaction temperature for the transesterification of TG to ethyl ester is considered to be around 80°C. As shown in Figure 6 , the yield of biodiesel was greatly dependent on the amount of catalyst applied. The FAEE content increased along with the increase in catalyst bed height, because the more catalyst available, the more molecules were absorbed onto the active center of the catalyst [CITATION_3] . The yield increased rapidly from 60.92% to 89.46% for PS and 57.45% to 83.32% for WCPO with the increase of the catalyst bed height from 150 to 300 mm. It demonstrates that a high catalyst bed height provides a longer residence time and more active sites to promote the reaction between TG and ethanol at a given flow rate [CITATION_4] . However, when the catalyst bed height exceeded 250 mm, the rate of reaction increased slightly. Therefore, the optimum catalyst bed height for biodiesel production in this research is found to be 250 mm.",
